          "logprobs": [],
          "text": "On January 12, 2026, corn futures experienced notable market activity. The Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT) reported a trading volume of 1,004,241 contracts, a significant increase from the previous day's volume of 295,762 contracts. Open interest stood at 1,533,892 contracts, reflecting a decrease of 2,167 contracts from the prior day. ([apnews.com](https://apnews.com/article/c3053400191c46d1c2a9b9a7a82970d6?utm_source=openai))\n\nThe market closed lower, with March corn futures down 24\u00bc cents at $4.21\u00bd per bushel. This decline was attributed to market reactions to the USDA's World Agricultural Supply and Demand Estimates (WASDE) report, which projected a record U.S. corn production of 17.0 billion bushels, leading to increased ending stocks and a downward adjustment in the season-average farm price to $4.10 per bushel. ([agriculture.com](https://www.agriculture.com/pre-report-markets-higher-or-monday-jan-12-2026-11883462?utm_source=openai))\n\nAdditionally, the Texas A&M AgriLife Extension Service's Feed Grain Outlook report highlighted a decrease in corn prices, noting that the March 2026 contract price fell from $4.38 on January 2 to $4.22 on January 12, a 3.66% decline. ([agecoext.tamu.edu](https://agecoext.tamu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2026/01/FG_2026-01-12.pdf?utm_source=openai))\n\n\n## Highlights:\n- [BC-Corn Futures](https://apnews.com/article/c3053400191c46d1c2a9b9a7a82970d6?utm_source=openai), Published on Monday, January 12\n- [BC-Corn Futures](https://apnews.com/article/7b998df9045c8000b0084f2a02e34d1e?utm_source=openai), Published on Tuesday, January 13 "
